{
  "texts": [
    "So regular open sets can refine regular open sets, and sets of pairs can refine sets of pairs, but regular open sets cannot refine sets of pairs or vice versa.",
    "Since ⟨℘(R 2), ⊆⟩ is a complete (and atomic) Boolean lattice, we have taken a disjoint union of two complete Boolean lattices-minus the bottom elements.",
    "Again, this makes it easy to deal with the set P of admissible propositions in our full possibility frame F. The regular open sets in the downset topology on our ⟨S, ⊑⟩ are just ∅ and for each O ∈ RO(R) \\ {∅} and σ ∈ ℘(R 2) \\ {∅}, the sets ↓O, ↓σ, and ↓O ∪ ↓σ.All that remains is to define the accessibility relations in F. Let R i be the universal relation on S. Before defining the other relations, let us explain the strategy to ensure that F validates an instance of (Split).Strategy.",
    "We will define a formula ψ such that ψ M = RO(R) \\ {∅} for any model M based on F. Thus, ♢ i (p ∧ ψ) will say that p is true at some regular open set, which with our observation above about the admissible sets in P implies that there is some regular open O such that p M ∩RO(R) = ↓O.",
    "Then we will define a formula φ such that for any modelM based on F, if p M ∩ RO(R) = ↓O, then φ M = ↓O -for O -as in (2.4)."
  ]
}